## Accessibility — WCAG 2.1 (POUR)

**Perceivable:** All images have alt text. Color alone never conveys info. Text contrast 4.5:1 (normal), 3:1 (large).

**Operable:** All functionality via keyboard. No keyboard traps. Focus order logical. Touch targets 44x44px min.

**Understandable:** Error messages identify issue and describe fix. Consistent navigation across pages.

**Robust:** Valid HTML. ARIA roles used correctly. Status messages programmatically determinable.

**Focus management:**
- Visible focus ring on all interactive elements (never outline:none without replacement)
- Modal opens: focus to first focusable element inside
- Modal closes: focus returns to trigger
- Dynamic content changes announced to screen readers

**Accessible forms:** All inputs have `<label>`. Errors via `aria-describedby`. Required = both visual + `aria-required`. Autocomplete on common fields.

**Accessible color:** Don't rely on color alone. Test with colorblindness simulators. Most common: red-green (supplement with icons).

---

## Dark Patterns — NEVER Implement

Confirmshaming, roach motels, hidden costs, misdirection, bait-and-switch, disguised ads, forced continuity, privacy zuckering, trick questions (double-negative checkboxes).

**The test:** Would you be embarrassed explaining this design decision directly to your user? If yes, it's a dark pattern.
